				\begin{document}$$ n^{{\frac{2}{3}}} $$\end{document} [23]. Indeed, despite the larger carrier density of the IZO-4 film compared to IZO-2, both films yield the same optical bandgap. Likewise, IZO-6 has a lower optical bandgap despite its larger carrier density compared to IZO-2. The bandgap assumes its lowest value among doped films for the IZO-8. This behavior may be explained with the argumentation of Sans et al., who stated that heavy doping of ZnO materials with In introduces anti-bonding indium–oxygen states [23]. These hybridize with the ZnO conduction band and lead to a downshift of the optical bandgap. This downshift scales with the In concentration in the film which can compensate the Burstein–Moss widening and gives rise to the observed trend of the optical bandgap versus In doping.
